    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-21T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="947"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d947">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.24/1726a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-21T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >January 21, 1944—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>118. From Batt. Representatives of U. S. S. R. requesting 30,000 tons aluminum
                    composed of 6,000 tons fabricated shapes, principally duralumin sheet, and
                    24,000 tons ingot for delivery prior to July 1. Account sharply reduced military
                    requirements here, we are now easily able to furnish these amounts. Our
                    willingness to comply will now be communicated to Soviet representatives. This,
                    together with amounts already committed, will make about 126,000 short tons
                    available during third Protocol period from Canada and United States.
                    [Batt.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
